Not considering sexuality as a large part of identity is rather dismissive I think. Ideally it is not, but reality is that it is. A lot of what we consider "dignity" or just cultural norms comes from the ability to fulfill gender roles. It's what makes coming of age stories so compelling and ubiquitous as a genre. I think everyone wants attention and validation to some degree or another from their preferred sex. It's part of our basic human need. More attention means more power and status. That in turn creates stronger influence and identity. Therein also lies the problem though. Not recognizing the true nature of our attention-seeking leads to infatuation and heartbreak. This is possibly reinforced by romantic notions that love hurts. How do people try to beat the system then? 
1. Break the sexuality binary and create new identities - LGBT
2. Seek the attention highs from other things - sufism, cars, porn, drugs (yup, that escalated quickly)
3. Become heartless and completely disregard attention taking and giving
4. Just give and give and give attention and let people walk all over you - what Haytham may call parent love
5. Just take and take and take attention and break many (heart) banks - what Haytham may call baby love
6. Embrace the give and take but minimise the ego while knowing love to be distinct - about choice and sacrifice, all the while being very open about it

*MAJOR ANNOUNCEMENT REVEAL*

Bismillah (In the name of God),

Day in and day out, we hear and see countless stories of young Muslims and milennials struggling with a myriad of issues.

Where does one go to talk about some of the most relevant and crucial problems of our day?  Where does one open up in an environment free from the ill-formed judgments of others?  How do we initiate the kind of dialogue needed to truly move forward and thrive as a community? As an Ummah? What is this post even getting at?

After much deliberation and much inspiration from the good fellows over at the @[440156896010823:274:MSA UBC] we are excited to present you with our very own rendition of...

SFU MSA's CHAT & CHAI!

Join us as we take part in a series of unfiltered, uncensored and authentic conversations on the issues YOU care about! What better way to spend an evening engaging with your fellow youth over a nice hot cup of chai? Details and topics for discussion will be released shortly. We're *certain* you won't be disappointed. Please note that this forum is open to everyone.
